beastiary:int_minotaur_dante a beast:Interpretation ;
    rdfs:comment "The Minotaur in Dante functions as a predominantly theriomorphic symbol of chaotic animality. His self-biting and self-lacerating rage exemplify the schema of devouring jaws turned inward: the beast consumes itself, becoming an image of violence that is both destructive and self-destructive. At the same time, Dante intensifies the symbol through a catamorphic register. The creature is located in the descending geography of Hell and is linked to the fall from reason into brute impulse."@en ;
    beast:appearsIn beastiary:source_dante_inferno ;
    beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure beast:SchizomorphicStructure ;
    beast:embodiesArchetype beastiary:archetype_guardian_hell,
        beastiary:archetype_violence ;
    beast:embodiesImaginarySymbol beast:CatamorphicSymbol,
        beast:TeriomorphicSymbol ;
    beast:hasTextualReference beastiary:citation_dante_inferno_1 ;
    beast:isGovernedBy beast:DiurnalRegime ;
    beast:ofCreature beastiary:creature_minotaur .

beastiary:int_minotaur_gospodinov a beast:Interpretation ;
    rdfs:comment "\"Gospodinov inverts the teriomorphic monster into a figure of intimacy: the terrifying beast as abandoned child alone and vulnerable at the center of the labyrinth, self sheltering within interiority. The labyrinth functions as an intimacy symbol, the cradle of abandoned childhood memory where time folds back on itself, allowing chilhood and present to coexist."@en ;
    beast:appearsIn beastiary:source_gospodinov_fisica_della_malinconia ;
    beast:belongsToImaginaryStructure beast:MysticalStructure ;
    beast:embodiesArchetype beastiary:archetype_abandoned_child,
        beastiary:archetype_shameful_offspring ;
    beast:embodiesImaginarySymbol beast:IntimacySymbol,
        beast:InversionSymbol ;
    beast:hasTextualReference beastiary:citation_gospodinov_1 ;
    beast:isGovernedBy beast:NocturnalRegime ;
    beast:ofCreature beastiary:creature_minotaur .

